To understand Docker containers, two Linux kernel features are very important:

Namespaces and Control Groups (cgroups).

They are the core technologies behind containers.

Namespaces → Isolation

PID Namespace (Process Isolation)
Each container has its own process list.

Example:

Container 1:

PID 1 → Spring Boot
PID 2 → JVM thread

Container 2:

PID 1 → MySQL
PID 2 → MySQL worker

Both containers have PID 1, but they are isolated.

Network Namespace

Each container has its own network stack.

Example:

Container 1 → IP 172.17.0.2
Container 2 → IP 172.17.0.3

Each container has:

its own IP

its own ports

its own network interfaces

Control groups (cgroups) control how much system resources a container can use.

They manage:

CPU

Memory

Disk I/O

Network

Without cgroups, one container could consume all resources and crash the system.

Example

Suppose your server has:

8 GB RAM
4 CPU cores

You run two containers:

Container 1 → Spring Boot
Container 2 → MySQL

Using cgroups you can set limits:

Spring Boot → 2GB RAM
MySQL → 3GB RAM

So Spring Boot cannot use more than 2GB RAM.